Th  e postoperative surveillance of patients treated 
for CRC is intended to prolong survival by diagnosing recur-rent and metachronous cancers at a curable stage, and to prevent metachronous cancer by detection and removal of precancerous polyps. Surveillance strategies employ  a combination of modalities, 
including history and physical examination, carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA), computed tomography (CT) scans, and endo-luminal imaging, including colonoscopy, sigmoidoscopy, endo-scopic ultrasound (EUS), and CT colonography (CTC).
